# Machine Learning Classification Concepts – Deep Dive

## Overview
This repository contains detailed notes and conceptual understanding of core Machine Learning classification algorithms studied as part of training.

The focus is on building strong intuition, understanding real-world applications, and preparing for technical discussions and evaluations.

---

## Topics Covered

### 1. Decision Tree
- Tree-based model using conditional logic
- Concepts: nodes, branches, leaves
- Splitting using Gini Index / Entropy
- Example: Loan approval system

---

### 2. Random Forest
- Ensemble method using multiple Decision Trees
- Concept of voting for final prediction
- Reduces overfitting and improves accuracy
- Real-world analogy: multiple experts deciding together

---

### 3. Support Vector Machine (SVM)
- Classification algorithm that finds the best separating boundary
- Focus on maximizing margin between classes
- Works well for high-dimensional data

---

### 4. Hyperplane
- Decision boundary used by SVM
- Line in 2D, plane in 3D, hyperplane in higher dimensions

---

### 5. Margin
- Distance between boundary and nearest data points
- Larger margin leads to better model performance

---

### 6. Support Vectors
- Closest points to the boundary
- Critical in defining the decision boundary

---

### 7. Naive Bayes
- Probability-based classification algorithm
- Based on Bayes theorem
- Assumes feature independence

---

### 8. Types of Naive Bayes
- Gaussian: Continuous data
- Multinomial: Text data
- Bernoulli: Binary data

---

### 9. Real-World Applications
- Spam detection
- Sentiment analysis
- Document classification
- Recommendation systems
- Medical diagnosis

---

### 10. Agentic Systems Memory
- AI systems using memory and tools
- Components: LLM, short-term memory, long-term memory, tools
- Enables adaptive and intelligent decision-making

---

## Key Learnings
- Understanding different classification algorithms and their working principles
- Identifying when to use each algorithm based on problem type
- Building intuition for model decision-making
- Connecting theory with real-world applications

---

## Conclusion
These concepts form the foundation of Machine
Learning classification techniques and are
essential for building robust predictive models and
preparing for technical interviews and evaluations.